Overview¶

Hofstede’s Dimensions¶

Author’s note: This work was performed as part of the Developing Data Skills course at the University of Edinburgh in spring 2021. Though effort was made to adequately research the background and theory behind the data studied, the author has no background in sociology and is ill-equipped to accurately evaluate the findings. As such, this work should be regarded as an exercise in data analysis and no real-world conclusions should be inferred.

Introduction¶

Geert Hofstede founded the personnel research department at IBM Europe in 1961, and between 1967 and 1973 conducted a large-scale worldwide survey of IBM employees for the purposes of determining difference in attitude across nations. These attitudes were initially categorised along four cultural dimensions: power distance, individualism, uncertainty avoidance, and masculinity. This work was published in his 1980 book Culture’s Consequences [1] and was intended to inform IBM’s policy regarding how to adapt management techniques and work environments across their global operation. Note that these cultural dimensions are equivalently referred to as cultural indices. Since then, these dimensions have formed a basic framework for cross-cultural studies and have been augmented to include the dimensions long-term orientation and indulgence where added following work performed by Michael Minkov [2], [3]. The work of Hofstede is today carried out by the Hofstede Institute which continues to study and refine the various indices (https://www.hofstede-insights.com).

Hofstede’s work is not without criticism. For instance, it has been proposed that a false equivalency is drawn between culture and nation, with many nations containing pronounced subcultures with significantly different values and attitudes [4]. Furthermore, while Hofstede makes it clear that no value-judgement is being made regarding the cultural dimensions [1], it has been argued that the lack of diversity on his research team resulted in an analysis that is inevitable white, male and Eurocentric [5]. The initial study was also accused of lacking rigor and containing too small sample sizes to draw conclusions regarding entire nations, with no consideration given to whether the sample was representative of the nation as a whole [6].

Nonetheless, his seminal work remains the most cited publication in the field of cross-cultural psychology [7] and has been widely applied since its publication (see [8], [9], [10] and references therein) and has been heralded even by its critics as “a super classic” [11]. The ambition of this project is to explore particularly pronounced cultural differences between countries and to examine correlations between these dimensions. In particular, the question prompting this analysis was “Which border, when crossed, gives one the largest culture shock?” where the culture shock will be assumed to be proportional to the difference in the cultural dimensions.

The Dimensions and Definitions¶

  1. Power Distance: the extent to which less powerful members of an organisation or institution accept and expect that power is distributed unequally. Examples of lower power distance behaviour are irreverence for authority figures and more equal income distributions, whereas high power distance is characterised by strong societal hierarchies.
  2. Uncertainty Avoidance: the extent to which individuals feel uncomfortable or comfortable in unstructured and unfamiliar situations. A high uncertainty avoidance is characterised by stricter behaviour codes and laws, and a disapproval of deviation. A low uncertainty avoidance results in a dislike of rules and acceptance of diverse moral and political frameworks.
  3. Individualism: individualism is opposed to collectivism and characterises the degree to which people in a society are integrated into groups such as family or the state. High collectivism is characterised belonging, harmony, and contribution to the group rather than individual priority and achievement.
  4. Masculinity: masculinity as opposed to femininity can be thought of the extent to which a country takes an egalitarian or feminist approach to societal structures; feminine/feminist societies tend to afford strong work-family balance, reduced segregation between male and female spaces, and promote women in positions of authority and power.
  5. Long-term orientation: this dimension characterises the propensity to maintain time-honoured traditions and norms while viewing societal change with suspicions. Short-term orientation is characterised by showing an ability to easily adapt traditions to changing conditions.
  6. Indulgence: People in societies classified by a high score in Indulgence generally exhibit a willingness to realise their impulses and desires regarding enjoying life and having fun. A low-indulgence society is characterized by restraint, putting less emphasis on leisure time and gratification.

Comments¶

So, there are a few themes here. Many dimensions exhibit an east-west gradient across the Eurasian landmass, with the individualism-collectivism axis being the most pronounced: China on one end being strongly collectivist and western Europe, particularly the UK, being strongly individualist. India is a slight outlier in this regard.

The analysis points towards individalism being strongly correlated with the influence of British colonilism, with the core anglosphere countries (UK, USA, Canada, Australia, New Zealand) all being in the top 10 most individualistic countries:

Define Culture Vector¶

For this project, we'll define a culture vector which will measure the magnitude of cultural difference between two countries, using the cultural indices. $${culture\_vector} = \begin{pmatrix} pdi \\ indv \\ masc \\ {unc\_av} \\ {lt\_ori} \\ indul \end{pmatrix}$$ Using this, we will calculate a $\Delta{culture\_vector}$ which represents the magnitude of the cultural difference between two countries. $$\Delta{culture\_vector}^2=\Delta{pdi}^2+\Delta{indv}^2+\Delta{masc}^2+\Delta{unc\_av}^2+\Delta{lt\_ori}^2+\Delta{indul}^2$$ In terms of code, define a function. Note that if any field is empty, it is simply ignored in the difference calculation.

In [40]:
def calc_cult_vector_diff(args):
    culture_dimensions = ['power_dist','individualism','masculinity','uncert_avoidance','lt_orientation','indulgence']
    lsuffix = '_country1'
    rsuffix = '_country2'
    """
    vector = np.array([args['power_dist_country1']-args['power_dist_country2'], 
                       args['individualism_country1']-args['individualism_country2'], 
                       args['masculinity_country1']-args['masculinity_country2'], 
                       args['uncert_avoidance_country1']-args['uncert_avoidance_country2'], 
                       args['lt_orientation_country1']-args['lt_orientation_country2'], 
                       args['indulgence_country1']-args['indulgence_country2']
                       ])
    """
    vector = args[[(dim+lsuffix) for dim in culture_dimensions]].values-args[[(dim+rsuffix) for dim in culture_dimensions]].values
    return pd.Series(data={'culture_vector_diff':np.sqrt(np.sum([np.square(x) for x in vector if not np.isnan(x)]))})

Steepest Borders¶

We are now in a position to actually determine the steepest border between countries.

There we are: the sharpest land-border in the world is the Russia-Norway border. Despite being a relatively long border at around 200 km, it is very scarcely populated. Furthermore, the centers of gravity of both countries are of course many kilometers away from this border, with the closest city with a population above 50,000 (Murmansk) in Russia being 110 km from the border, and the closest Norwegian city with a population above 50,000 (Tromso) being 430 km away.

We would intuit that factors influencing this sharpness is the population density close to the border, along with the size of the country; a smaller country with a high population density close to border might have been conducive the high volumes of cultural exchange between the countries.

Regardless, it perhaps not a surprise that the sharpest border according to this analysis is between an EEC country and the former USSR, two economic and societal orders which differ significantly. As we can see, Russia also has a very sharp border with Finland, another Nordic country which indeed fought a hot war with Russia in the years 1939-40.
